  "prompt": "What is the difference between Shall and Will?",
  "response": "The words \"shall\" and \"will\" are both used to indicate future tense, but there are some subtle differences in their usage, particularly in formal contexts:\n\n1. **Traditional Usage**: \n   - \"Shall\" is often used with the first person (I and we) to express future actions or intentions, while \"will\" is typically used with the second and third persons (you, he, she, it, they). \n     - Example: \"I shall go to the store.\" / \"He will go to the store.\"\n  \n2. **Modern Usage**: \n   - In contemporary English, \"will\" has largely replaced \"shall\" in both formal and informal contexts, even with the first person. Most speakers and writers use \"will\" regardless of the subject.\n     - Example: \"I will go to the store.\"\n\n3. **Formality and Obligation**:\n   - \"Shall\" can carry a sense of formality, obligation, or determination, especially in legal or official documents. For instance, \"The tenant shall pay rent by the first of each month.\"\n   - \"Will\" simply indicates a future action or intention without the same level of formality. \n\n4. **Suggestions and Offers**:\n   - \"Shall\" is sometimes used to make suggestions or offers, especially in questions. \n     - Example: \"Shall we go for a walk?\" \n   - \"Will\" is less commonly used in this way, though it can still be used to indicate willingness.\n     - Example: \"Will you help me?\"\n\nIn summary, while \"shall\" and \"will\" can often be used interchangeably in modern English, \"shall\" tends to be more formal and may imply obligation or suggestion, while \"will\" is the more commonly used term for indicating future actions.",
